results.notes:
Growing in leaf litter under Rhododendron catawbiense, Vaccinium corymbosum, and scattered Picea rubens. Caps up to 10.5 mm wide and 6.6 mm tall; dry. Gills adnexed to arcuate or short-decurrent. Stems up to 45.3 mm long and 1.3 mm wide; slimy and smooth. Not noticeably bioluminescent. Not noticeably fluorescent under UV light. Odor not distinctive to slightly raphanoid. Taste not distinctive. Lamellar trama dextrinoid. Cheilocystidia scattered; hyaline; clavate-roughened. Basidia 2-sterigmate or 4-sterigmate, some with very long sterigmata. Spores weakly amyloid; pip-shaped; hyaline; smooth; thin-walled. Spore measurements: (6.5) 7.3 – 9.9 (12.6) (3.4) 3.8 – 4.7 (4.9) m; Q = (1.6) 1.7 – 2.3 (2.9); N = 30; Me = 8.5 4.2 m; Qe = 2

results.notes:
Growing scattered on Rhododendron catawbiense leaves. Caps dry; canescent; up to 5.5 mm wide and 6.5 mm tall. Gills adnexed. Stems dry; smooth; up to 26.7 mm long and 1.0 mm wide. Not noticeably bioluminescent. Not noticeably fluorescent under UV light. Odor not distinctive. Lamellar trama strongly dextrinoid. Pleurocystidia absent. Cheilocystidia forming a sterile band; clavate-roughened; hyaline. Basidia 2-sterigmate. Spores weakly amyloid, hyaline, smooth, thin-walled. Spore measurements: (5.6) 5.9 – 8.3 (9.3) (2.9) 3.2 – 4.2 (4.7) m; Q = (1.5) 1.7 – 2.1 (2.9); N = 30; Me = 6.8 3.6 m; Qe = 1.9

results.notes:
2 basidiocarps growing on a Rhododendron catawbiense leaf, 1 lost. Remaining basidiocarp with cap 1.4 mm wide and 0.7 mm tall. Gills adnate. Stems with yellowish-brown bases; 10.0 mm long and 0.2 mm wide in remaining basidiocarp. Not noticeably bioluminescent. Not noticeably fluorescent under UV light. Lamellar trama dextrinoid. Clamps and lactifers present in the pilear trama. Clamps present in the lamellar trama. Pleurocystidia absent or rare. Cheilocystidia abundant, hyaline, smooth, fusoid-ventricose or with forked apices, basally clamped. Basidia 2-sterigmate, clavate, basally clamped. Spores weakly amyloid, hyaline, smooth, and thin-walled. Spore measurements: (7.5) 9.7 – 11.6 (11.9) (3.9) 4.4 – 5.2 (5.5) m; Q = (1.9) 2 – 2.5 (2.7); N = 30; Me = 10.5 4.7 m; Qe = 2.2

results.notes:
Growing on a fallen Lonicera maackii twig. Caps white (7.5YR 8.5/1 in Munsell) when young becoming very pale brown (10YR 8/2); dry; up to 5.8 mm wide and 3.0 mm tall. Gills white (7.5YR 8.5/1) at the youngest, becoming pale orange yellow (10YR 9.5/2) before becoming yellow in age (10YR 8/6); adnate. Stems dark bluish gray (10B 4/1); up to 15.7 mm long and 0.5 mm wide. Odor not distinctive. Taste slightly sweet. Not bioluminescent.

results.notes:
Growing abundantly on piles of small hardwood debris in the floodplain of Third Creek near Platanus occidentalis, Acer negundo, Acer sacchariferm, Ulmus sp., Salix nigra, Fraxinus sp., Rhamnus cathartica, Lonicera maacki, and Campsis radicans. Caps dry; glabrous; translucent-striate; up to 19.6 mm wide and 3.2 mm tall. Gills short-decurrent; frequently forking. Stems smooth; up to 9.8 mm long and 1.0 mm wide. Associated with whitish rhizomorphs binding woody debris together. Odor not distinctive. Taste not distinctive. Not bioluminescent. Lamellar trama inamyloid. Clamps present in the lamellar trama. Lamellar cystidia not clearly differentiated. Basidia 4-sterigmate. Spores, inamyloid, hyaline, smooth, and thin-walled. Spore measurements: (6.8) 6.9 – 8.3 (9.3) (3.4) 3.7 – 4.3 (4.6) m; Q = (1.7) 1.8 – 2 (2.1); N = 9; Me = 7.7 4.1 m; Qe = 1.9

results.notes:
Habitat: semi-ruderal grassland, under a canopy of Juglans regia next to an abandoned farmhouse; locally almost flat terrain, calcareous, skeletal, colluvial ground; mostly in shade; partly protected from direct rain by tree canopies; average precipitations ~ 3.000 mm/year, average temperature 7-9 deg C, elevation 555 m (1.820 feet), alpine phytogeographical region; pictures taken after a prolonged rainy period.

Substratum: soil, leaf litter, organic debris.

Place: Lower Trenta valley, between villages Soa and Trenta, right bank of river Soa, near the abandoned farmhouse Skokar, Trenta 2; East Julian Alps, Posoje, Slovenia.

Description: Two pilei present; hydrophanous; diameter of the larger 6.3 cm, stipe firm, fibrous, hollow, flexuous, 8 cm long, and about 9 mm in diameter; smell and taste faint, mushroomy; SP abundant, light beige with a slight yellow-greenish tint, oac892. The measured spore dimensions do not correspond to expectations. They are significantly too narrow (see Fig. 2M). I have no explanation for this.

results.notes:
Growing scattered on hardwood bark and twigs. Locally abundant. Caps 2.2 to 4.2 cm wide. Gills adnate or adnexed. Stems hollow. Stems 2.5 to 6.6 cm long and 0.2 to 0.4 cm wide. Clear guttation present on the bases of some stems. All surfaces drying pale orange. Odor not distinctive to slightly spermatic. Spore print white. Clamps present in the lamellar trama. Pleurocystidia scattered and similar to the cheilocystidia. Cheilocystidia abundant, hyaline, smooth, thin-walled, mostly lageniform and frequently with flexuose apices, forming a sterile margin. Spores inamyloid, hyaline, smooth, and thin-walled, frequently germinating on the gills. Spore measurements: (10.1) 10.5 – 13 (14.2) (3.5) 3.6 – 4.8 (5.2) m; Q = (2.2) 2.5 – 3.2 (3.4); N = 30; Me = 11.9 4.2 m; Qe = 2.8

—

results.notes:
Growing scattered on hardwood twigs with black rhizomorphs. Locally abundant. Caps 0.6 to 2.2 cm wide. Stems 0.7 to 1.6 cm long and 0.1 cm wide. Slowly drying yellowish-orange. Odor not distinctive. Caps and gills turning brown after drying (examined in February 2024). Spore print white. Pileipellis covered with pileocystidia similar in morphology to the lamellar cystidia. Clamps present in the lamellar trama. Pleurocystidia and cheilocystidia present. Cheilocystidia hyaline; smooth; lageniform, utriform, fusiform, or tibiiform; appearing yellow in dried basidiocarps at low magnification. Basidia 4-sterigmate and basally clamped. Spores hyaline, smooth, and thin-walled. Spore measurements: (7.5) 12.1 – 16.7 (17.6) (3.5) 3.9 – 5.7 (7.3) m; Q = (1.9) 2.6 – 3.6 (4.3); N = 30; Me = 14.1 4.7 m; Qe = 3

results.notes:
Fruiting in needle litter bark chips beneath Douglas fir.
Stem: covered in scales, especially heavily scabrose toward apex.
Cap: pruinose/hygrophanous but coated in fine granulose elements. Darker at disc.
Gills: grayish purple. Partial/incomplete gills abundant. Slightly decurrent attachment. Gill margin with abundant white cystidia.
Harvested first specimen and then three more approximately 10 minutes later from a few yards away.
Harvested all 4 specimens.
Spore printed a single cap directly on a glass slide for spore print(Slide#1).
Slide #2: removed a single gill from mature cap and mounted in 3% KOH.
MICROSCOPY:
Slide#2(Gill mount):
Pleurocystidia: large, round(broadly turbinate) abundant on gill edge. Golden yellow marginal walls in KOH.
Cheilocystidia: lageniform to awl shaped, large. Less abundant than Pleurocystidia but not scarce.
Spores: Ellipsoid to narrowly Ellipsoid, some nearly cylindrical, smooth walled, apical germ pore, purplish gray brown color in KOH, Small.
Lamellar Trama: cellular, roundish cells abundant.
Basidia: 4 sterigmate.
Slide #1: Spore printed Slide:
Spore Print: Dark Purple Brown.
Mounted spore printed slide in 3% KOH.
Spores: Ellipsoid to narrowly Ellipsoid, some nearly cylindrical, smooth walled, apical germ pore, purplish gray brown color in KOH, Small.
Dehydrated all 4 specimens and bagged with dessicant pack for herbarium collection/genetic record.
Spore shape and features, Pleurocystidia, cheilocystidia in addition to dark purple brown spore print and macromorphological features put this in Psathyrellaceae(additionally based on scaly stem and granulose pilei looking at possibly Cystoagaricus).
